        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 1: The shift -->
      <div class="cd-section">
        <div class="cd-section-hdr">
          <span class="cd-section-lbl"><i class="ti ti-h-2"></i>Section 1 · The shift</span>
          <div class="cd-section-controls">
            <button class="cd-section-ctrl"><i class="ti ti-wand"></i>Ask CRO</button>
            <button class="cd-section-ctrl"><i class="ti ti-refresh"></i>Regen</button>
          </div>
        </div>
        <h2 class="cd-h2" contenteditable="true">The shift: from "AI works" to "AI you can defend"</h2>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true">Two years ago, federal capture teams were asking whether AI could read solicitations. Today, that's solved. The new question is sharper: can your AI tell you <em>why</em> it surfaced what it surfaced? And can it tell that story to an inspector general, six months after the contract awarded?</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true">This is the explainability mandate. Six federal CIOs have now published versions of it — at Treasury, DOE, Commerce, VA, GSA, and most recently DoD's Defense Innovation Unit. The mandates aren't identical, but they share a structure: every AI-generated artifact in a procurement context needs a traceable source chain, a reviewable decision log, and a human checkpoint before it leaves the building.</p>
        <div class="cd-grounding">
          <span class="cd-grounding-lbl"><i class="ti ti-link"></i>Grounded in</span>
          <span class="cd-chunk"><span class="cd-chunk-dot sig"></span>sg-12 · CIO mandates</span>
          <span class="cd-chunk"><span class="cd-chunk-dot ext"></span>Treasury memo</span>
          <span class="cd-chunk"><span class="cd-chunk-dot ext"></span>DIU directive</span>
          <span class="cd-chunk"><span class="cd-chunk-dot cust"></span>Customer interview · Lockheed</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: What audit-defensible actually means -->
      <div class="cd-section">
        <div class="cd-section-hdr">
          <span class="cd-section-lbl"><i class="ti ti-h-2"></i>Section 2 · The standard</span>
          <div class="cd-section-controls">
            <button class="cd-section-ctrl"><i class="ti ti-wand"></i>Ask CRO</button>
            <button class="cd-section-ctrl"><i class="ti ti-refresh"></i>Regen</button>
          </div>
        </div>
        <h2 class="cd-h2" contenteditable="true">What audit-defensible actually means — three load-bearing requirements</h2>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>Source attribution at the claim level.</strong> Not "this section was AI-generated." Specifically: this sentence was derived from these clauses in the solicitation, weighted this way. Without claim-level provenance, you have a generated artifact you cannot defend in an audit.</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>A reviewable decision log.</strong> Every action the AI took, in order, with the inputs it had at the time. Including the actions a human approved or rejected. Federal audit doesn't accept "the model decided." It needs "the model proposed X, the human approved at 14:32, here's the input state."</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>Human-in-the-loop by default, not as an option.</strong> The Forrester Wave for HITL Federal AI (Q1 '26) made this dimension load-bearing for a reason: vendors that treat human review as a configurable feature fail the audit standard. Vendors that treat it as architectural — where no AI artifact leaves the system without a recorded human checkpoint — pass.</p>
        <div class="cd-grounding">
          <span class="cd-grounding-lbl"><i class="ti ti-link"></i>Grounded in</span>
