        <h2 class="cd-h2" contenteditable="true">Three questions every capture lead should ask their AI vendor this quarter</h2>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true">If you're evaluating capture AI right now, the demo isn't the test. The audit walkthrough is the test. Three questions surface whether a tool is actually audit-defensible or whether it just looks polished on a slide.</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>One: "Show me the provenance for this sentence."</strong> Pick any generated paragraph in their demo. Ask them to surface the exact source material the AI used to produce it. If the answer is "the model" or "the training data," that vendor cannot pass a federal audit.</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>Two: "Walk me through the action log from this morning."</strong> If they can show you a chronological log of every AI action, every input state, and every human checkpoint, you're looking at an architecture built for audit. If they can't pull that log, the architecture isn't there.</p>
        <p class="cd-body-p" contenteditable="true"><strong>Three: "What happens when a reviewer rejects an AI suggestion?"</strong> In an audit-defensible system, that rejection becomes a logged event with reasoning. In a less defensible system, the suggestion just goes away. The difference matters — IG auditors care about the rejections as much as the approvals.</p>
